<h2>HVAC Systems in Connecticut</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Connecticut's humid continental climate presents unique challenges for HVAC systems, requiring equipment that can efficiently handle both heating and cooling demands. The state experiences average winter temperatures ranging from 20¬∞F to 40¬∞F, with occasional periods dropping below 0¬∞F, necessitating robust heating capabilities. Summer temperatures typically range from 70¬∞F to 85¬∞F with high humidity levels, creating substantial cooling and dehumidification requirements. This climate profile makes heat pumps an increasingly popular choice, as modern cold-climate heat pumps can efficiently operate in temperatures as low as -15¬∞F while providing both heating and cooling functions.</p>

<p>For Connecticut homes, HVAC professionals typically recommend systems with SEER ratings of 16-20 for air conditioning units and HSPF ratings of 9.0-10.0 for heat pumps. These efficiency ratings ensure optimal performance while minimizing energy consumption during peak demand periods. Due to the state's heating-dominant climate, homeowners should prioritize heating efficiency over cooling efficiency when selecting HVAC equipment. Central air conditioning systems with variable-speed compressors and multi-stage heat pumps are particularly well-suited for Connecticut's climate, as they can adjust capacity based on real-time demand while maintaining consistent indoor comfort levels.</p>

