<h2>Connecticut Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Connecticut offers one of the most comprehensive incentive packages in the nation for solar and energy-efficient HVAC systems. The cornerstone of these incentives is the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, homeowners can claim a \$6,000 federal tax credit, significantly reducing the net system cost.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> Available through 2032, this credit can be carried forward if the tax liability is insufficient in the installation year. The credit covers solar panels, inverters, mounting equipment, installation labor, and electrical upgrades necessary for the solar system. Homeowners must own their solar system to qualify, and the credit applies to both primary and secondary residences.</li>
<li><strong>SMART-E Loan Program:</strong> Connecticut's Residential Solar Investment Program offers low-interest financing for solar installations. The program provides loans up to \$40,000 with interest rates as low as 1.99% for qualified borrowers. This financing option makes solar accessible to homeowners who want to avoid upfront costs while still owning their system and claiming tax credits.</li>
<li><strong>Eversource Rebates and Programs:</strong> Eversource offers substantial rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment through their Home Energy Solutions program. Rebates include up to \$1,500 for ENERGY STAR certified heat pumps, \$1,000 for high-efficiency central air conditioning systems, and \$750 for smart thermostats. The utility also provides free energy audits and weatherization services.</li>
<li><strong>Connecticut Green Bank Financing:</strong> The nation's first green bank offers residential financing programs for solar and energy efficiency upgrades. Their CPACE program provides long-term financing tied to the property rather than the homeowner, making upgrades transferable to new owners and enabling larger projects.</li>
<li><strong>Net Metering Policy:</strong> Connecticut's net metering program provides full retail credit for excess solar production, allowing homeowners to offset 100% of their electricity consumption. Systems up to 20kW qualify for net metering, and excess credits can be carried forward indefinitely, providing maximum value for solar production.</li>
</ul>

